Shortest working implementation without using promises.

Why not Promise.all? - It is not a good choice here because each iterateeFn can have different execution time. And we want to start executing next iterateeFn as soon as number of current iterateeFn running is less than limit. For eg: if iterateeFn take time 1s, 2s, 3s, 4s, and 5s then Promise.all implementation will take 11s and below approach will take 9s. So, below approach is more optimized one.

What it does? -  It wraps callback function that we pass to iterateeFn to store result into proper index of allResults array. And as soon as we are getting result from iterateeFn, a new iterateeFn will be called if all inputs have not been processed.

```
function getNameById(id, callback) {
  const randomRequestTime = Math.floor(Math.random() * 100) + 200;
  setTimeout(() => {
    callback("User" + id)
  }, randomRequestTime);
}

function mapLimit(inputs, limit, iterateeFn, callback) {
  let numFuncsFinished = 0;
  const allResults = new Array(inputs.length);
  let i = 0;

  const callbackWrapper = function(index) {
    return (res) => {
      allResults[index] = res;
      numFuncsFinished++;
      if(numFuncsFinished == inputs.length) {
        callback(allResults);
      }
      if(i < inputs.length) {
        iterateeFn(inputs[i], callbackWrapper(i));
        i++;
      }
    }
  }

  while(i < limit && i < inputs.length) {
    iterateeFn(inputs[i], callbackWrapper(i));
    i++;
  }
}

mapLimit([1,2,3,4,5], 2, getNameById, (allResults) => {
  console.log('output:', allResults) // ["User1", "User2", "User3", "User4", "User5"]
});
```

